<subSubSection id="2BDCB0CCFFA4FF8DEF99FA42308DF906" pageId="22" pageNumber="71" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="6379E347FFA4FF8DEF99FA42325AFA47" blockId="22.[189,310,1444,1470]" box="[189,310,1444,1470]" pageId="22" pageNumber="71">
<heading id="3831542BFFA4FF8DEF99FA42325AFA47" bold="true" box="[189,310,1444,1470]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="22" pageNumber="71" reason="3">
<emphasis id="51B23F55FFA4FF8DEF99FA42325AFA47" bold="true" box="[189,310,1444,1470]" pageId="22" pageNumber="71">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6379E347FFA4FF8DEF99FA31308DF906" blockId="22.[189,1399,1495,1791]" pageId="22" pageNumber="71">Halopteridids with monosiphonic hydrocladia arising directly from creeping stolons. Hydrocladia branched, with several cladia originating dorsally from the distal parts of its ahydrothecate internodes. All cladia directed towards the same side or arranged either alternately or irregularly left and right along the stem. Branches of second and third order frequent in, at least, one species. Hydrothecate internodes with one hydrotheca, two pairs of lateral nematothecae and one mesial inferior nematotheca. Ahydrothecate internodes with a variable number of nematothecae. Hydrotheca partly adnate to its corresponding internode, cup-shaped, with untoothed rim. All nematothecae conical, bithalamic and movable. Gonothecae provided with nematothecae on the basal part.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2BDCB0CCFFA4FF8DEF99F8CF32A4F811" pageId="22" pageNumber="71" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="6379E347FFA4FF8DEF99F8CF3228F8BA" blockId="22.[189,324,1833,1859]" box="[189,324,1833,1859]" pageId="22" pageNumber="71">
<heading id="3831542BFFA4FF8DEF99F8CF3228F8BA" bold="true" box="[189,324,1833,1859]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="22" pageNumber="71" reason="3">
<emphasis id="51B23F55FFA4FF8DEF99F8CF3228F8BA" bold="true" box="[189,324,1833,1859]" pageId="22" pageNumber="71">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6379E347FFA4FF8DEF99F8BD32A4F811" blockId="22.[188,1399,1883,2025]" pageId="22" pageNumber="71">
The generic name 
<taxonomicName id="A4C698C4FFA4FF8DEEBDF8BD310AF88C" authorityName="Gil &amp; Ramil" authorityYear="2021" box="[409,614,1883,1909]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Halopterididae" genus="Monostaechoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="22" pageNumber="71" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="51B23F55FFA4FF8DEEBDF8BD310AF88C" box="[409,614,1883,1909]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="71">Monostaechoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is derived from a combination of the generic name 
<taxonomicName id="A4C698C4FFA4FF8DEBEAF8BD320AF862" authority="Allman, 1877" authorityName="Allman" authorityYear="1877" class="Hydrozoa" family="Halopterididae" genus="Monostaechas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="22" pageNumber="71" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="51B23F55FFA4FF8DEBEAF8BD361BF88C" box="[1230,1399,1883,1909]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="71">Monostaechas</emphasis>
Allman, 1877
</taxonomicName>
, and the latinized form of the Greek word-forming element ‘- 
<emphasis id="51B23F55FFA4FF8DEB4AF86737C6F862" box="[1134,1194,1921,1947]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="71">eidés</emphasis>
’, meaning ‘like, resembling’ and referring to the affinities of the new taxon with the genus 
<taxonomicName id="A4C698C4FFA4FF8DEB38F84E37A9F83B" authorityName="Allman" authorityYear="1877" box="[1052,1221,1960,1986]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Halopterididae" genus="Monostaechas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="22" pageNumber="71" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="51B23F55FFA4FF8DEB38F84E37A9F83B" box="[1052,1221,1960,1986]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="71">Monostaechas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The gender of the name is masculine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2BDCB0CCFFA5FF8CEF99FEEF378EF810" pageId="23" pageNumber="72" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="6379E347FFA5FF8CEF99FEEF3243FEDA" blockId="23.[189,303,265,291]" box="[189,303,265,291]" pageId="23" pageNumber="72">
<heading id="3831542BFFA5FF8CEF99FEEF3243FEDA" bold="true" box="[189,303,265,291]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="23" pageNumber="72" reason="3">
<emphasis id="51B23F55FFA5FF8CEF99FEEF3243FEDA" bold="true" box="[189,303,265,291]" pageId="23" pageNumber="72">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6379E347FFA5FF8CEF99FEDD3604FE5D" blockId="23.[189,1399,315,421]" pageId="23" pageNumber="72">
The presence of hydrothecae on the hydrocaulus is the main defining character of the family 
<taxonomicName id="A4C698C4FFA5FF8CEF99FE85317BFE84" authority="Millard, 1962" authorityName="Millard" authorityYear="1962" box="[189,535,355,381]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Halopterididae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="23" pageNumber="72" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="family">
Halopterididae 
<bibRefCitation id="07579EB6FFA5FF8CEE50FE85317BFE84" author="Millard N. A. H." box="[372,535,355,381]" pageId="23" pageNumber="72" pagination="261 - 319" refId="ref23639" refString="Millard N. A. H. 1962. The Hydrozoa of the south and west coasts of South Africa. Part I. The Plumulariidae. Annals of the South African Museum 46 (11): 261 - 319." type="journal article" year="1962">Millard, 1962</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="07579EB6FFA5FF8CED0CFE8531A4FE84" author="Millard N. A. H." box="[552,712,355,381]" pageId="23" pageNumber="72" pagination="261 - 319" refId="ref23639" refString="Millard N. A. H. 1962. The Hydrozoa of the south and west coasts of South Africa. Part I. The Plumulariidae. Annals of the South African Museum 46 (11): 261 - 319." type="journal article" year="1962">Millard 1962</bibRefCitation>
, 1975; 
<bibRefCitation id="07579EB6FFA5FF8CEC05FE8530B1FE84" author="Schuchert P." box="[801,989,355,381]" pageId="23" pageNumber="72" pagination="1 - 161" refId="ref25254" refString="Schuchert P. 1997. Review of the family Halopterididae (Hydrozoa, Cnidaria). Zoologische Verhandelingen, Leiden 309: 1 - 161." type="journal article" year="1997">Schuchert 1997</bibRefCitation>
), and the generic limits within the family are largely based on the shape of the colonies and their ramification patterns (
<bibRefCitation id="07579EB6FFA5FF8CEBBAFE6C3637FE5D" author="Schuchert P." box="[1182,1371,394,420]" pageId="23" pageNumber="72" pagination="1 - 161" refId="ref25254" refString="Schuchert P. 1997. Review of the family Halopterididae (Hydrozoa, Cnidaria). Zoologische Verhandelingen, Leiden 309: 1 - 161." type="journal article" year="1997">Schuchert 1997</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6379E347FFA5FF8CEF99FE3630B7FD71" blockId="23.[188,1399,464,649]" pageId="23" pageNumber="72">
The new genus described herein is characterized by having monosiphonic stems or primary hydrocladia arising from hydrorhiza and supporting irregularly pinnate or unilaterally-arranged secondary hydrocladia that, in turn, can originate hydrocladia of second and third order, in at least the 
<typeStatus id="BC7D5DE5FFA5FF8CEBC5FDC63678FDC3" box="[1249,1300,544,570]" pageId="23" pageNumber="72">type</typeStatus>
species. Another distinctive feature is the origin of the subsidiary hydrocladia from the postero-distal parts of ahydrothecate internodes, on the backside of an oblique distal node.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6379E347FFA5FF8CEF99FD523116FCE4" blockId="23.[189,1398,692,797]" pageId="23" pageNumber="72">
The general habit of the colonies, with single monosiphonic stems carrying laterally-placed hydrocladia, resembles those of 
<taxonomicName id="A4C698C4FFA5FF8CED2CFD3D3055FD0F" authority="Allman, 1877" authorityName="Allman" authorityYear="1877" box="[520,825,731,758]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Halopterididae" genus="Halopteris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="23" pageNumber="72" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="51B23F55FFA5FF8CED2CFD3D31E9FD0C" box="[520,645,731,757]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="72">Halopteris</emphasis>
Allman, 1877
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A4C698C4FFA5FF8CEC6EFD3D37C9FD0F" authority="Allman, 1877" authorityName="Allman" authorityYear="1877" box="[842,1189,731,758]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Halopterididae" genus="Monostaechas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="23" pageNumber="72" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="51B23F55FFA5FF8CEC6EFD3D309FFD0C" box="[842,1011,731,757]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="72">Monostaechas</emphasis>
Allman, 1877
</taxonomicName>
and the recently described 
<taxonomicName id="A4C698C4FFA5FF8CEE11FCE5311AFCE4" authority="Galea, 2020" authorityName="Galea" authorityYear="2020" box="[309,630,771,797]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Halopterididae" genus="Thamnopteros" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="23" pageNumber="72" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="51B23F55FFA5FF8CEE11FCE532B1FCE4" box="[309,477,771,797]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="72">Thamnopteros</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="07579EB6FFA5FF8CEEC0FCE5311AFCE4" author="Galea H. R. &amp; Maggioni D." box="[484,630,771,797]" pageId="23" pageNumber="72" pagination="1 - 58" refId="ref21587" refString="Galea H. R. &amp; Maggioni D. 2020. Plumularioid hydroids (Cnidaria: Hydrozoa) from off New Caledonia collected during KANACONO and KANADEEP expeditions of the French Tropical Deep-Sea Benthos Program. European Journal of Taxonomy 708: 1 - 58. https: // doi. org / 10.5852 / ejt. 2020.708" type="journal article" year="2020">Galea, 2020</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6379E347FFA5FF8CEF99FCAF3019FBF8" blockId="23.[189,1398,841,1025]" pageId="23" pageNumber="72">
Resemblances with 
<taxonomicName id="A4C698C4FFA5FF8CEE97FCAF315CFC9A" authorityName="Allman" authorityYear="1877" box="[435,560,841,867]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Halopterididae" genus="Halopteris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="23" pageNumber="72" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="51B23F55FFA5FF8CEE97FCAF315CFC9A" box="[435,560,841,867]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="72">Halopteris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are found in the ramified nature of the colonies belonging to both genera, but in 
<taxonomicName id="A4C698C4FFA5FF8CEE49FC963286FC73" authorityName="Allman" authorityYear="1877" box="[365,490,880,906]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Halopterididae" genus="Halopteris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="23" pageNumber="72" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="51B23F55FFA5FF8CEE49FC963286FC73" box="[365,490,880,906]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="72">Halopteris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the hydrocladia are routinely arranged in either alternate or opposite pairs, and originate from the hydrothecate internodes of the stem, laterally to the hydrothecae. 
<taxonomicName id="A4C698C4FFA5FF8CEBEAFC7E361AFC4B" authorityName="Galea" authorityYear="2020" box="[1230,1398,920,946]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Halopterididae" genus="Thamnopteros" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="23" pageNumber="72" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="51B23F55FFA5FF8CEBEAFC7E361AFC4B" box="[1230,1398,920,946]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="72">Thamnopteros</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
builds polysiphonic colonies giving rise to monosiphonic branchlets bearing pinnate hydrocladia with the same origin as in 
<taxonomicName id="A4C698C4FFA5FF8CEE93FC01301DFBF8" authority="(Galea &amp; Maggioni 2020)" baseAuthorityName="Galea &amp; Maggioni" baseAuthorityYear="2020" box="[439,881,999,1025]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Halopterididae" genus="Halopteris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="23" pageNumber="72" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="51B23F55FFA5FF8CEE93FC013158FBF8" box="[439,564,999,1025]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="72">Halopteris</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="07579EB6FFA5FF8CED60FC013005FBF8" author="Galea H. R. &amp; Maggioni D." box="[580,873,999,1025]" pageId="23" pageNumber="72" pagination="1 - 58" refId="ref21587" refString="Galea H. R. &amp; Maggioni D. 2020. Plumularioid hydroids (Cnidaria: Hydrozoa) from off New Caledonia collected during KANACONO and KANADEEP expeditions of the French Tropical Deep-Sea Benthos Program. European Journal of Taxonomy 708: 1 - 58. https: // doi. org / 10.5852 / ejt. 2020.708" type="journal article" year="2020">Galea &amp; Maggioni 2020</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6379E347FFA5FF8CEF99FBCA302FFA52" blockId="23.[189,1400,1068,1451]" pageId="23" pageNumber="72">
The new genus shows more affinities with 
<taxonomicName id="A4C698C4FFA5FF8CED90FBCA3769FBBE" authority="Allman, 1877" authorityName="Allman" authorityYear="1877" box="[692,1029,1068,1095]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Halopterididae" genus="Monostaechas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="23" pageNumber="72" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="51B23F55FFA5FF8CED90FBCA3031FBBF" box="[692,861,1068,1094]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="72">Monostaechas</emphasis>
Allman, 
<quantity id="A43E4EA2FFA5FF8CECEEFBCB3769FBBE" box="[970,1029,1069,1095]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.76758" pageId="23" pageNumber="72" unit="in" value="1877.0">1877</quantity>
</taxonomicName>
in both the origin of subsidiary hydrocladia on the postero-distal part of ahydrothecate internodes, just behind the distal oblique node, and the tendency to a unilateral disposition of subsidiary hydrocladia. Nevertheless, in 
<taxonomicName id="A4C698C4FFA5FF8CEBEBFB9D3614FB6C" authorityName="Allman" authorityYear="1877" box="[1231,1400,1147,1173]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Halopterididae" genus="Monostaechas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="23" pageNumber="72" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="51B23F55FFA5FF8CEBEBFB9D3614FB6C" box="[1231,1400,1147,1173]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="72">Monostaechas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the ramification pattern is a helicoid or scorpioid sympodium, in which each subsidiary hydrocladium originates from the postero-distal part of the first ahydrothecate internode of the previous hydrocladium (
<bibRefCitation id="07579EB6FFA5FF8CEFE1FB143233FAF5" author="Billard A." box="[197,351,1266,1292]" pageId="23" pageNumber="72" pagination="1 - 115" refId="ref19733" refString="Billard A. 1913. Les hydroides de l'expedition du Siboga, I. Plumulariidae. Siboga-Expeditie 7: 1 - 115." type="journal article" year="1913">Billard 1913</bibRefCitation>
; Millard 1975; 
<bibRefCitation id="07579EB6FFA5FF8CED3DFB1431B9FAF5" author="Schuchert P." box="[537,725,1266,1292]" pageId="23" pageNumber="72" pagination="1 - 161" refId="ref25254" refString="Schuchert P. 1997. Review of the family Halopterididae (Hydrozoa, Cnidaria). Zoologische Verhandelingen, Leiden 309: 1 - 161." type="journal article" year="1997">Schuchert 1997</bibRefCitation>
), resulting in a false axis composed of the basal parts of successive hydrocladia (
<bibRefCitation id="07579EB6FFA5FF8CEEC7FAFC3113FACD" author="Billard A." box="[483,639,1306,1332]" pageId="23" pageNumber="72" pagination="1 - 115" refId="ref19733" refString="Billard A. 1913. Les hydroides de l'expedition du Siboga, I. Plumulariidae. Siboga-Expeditie 7: 1 - 115." type="journal article" year="1913">Billard 1913</bibRefCitation>
; Millard 1975). In 
<taxonomicName id="A4C698C4FFA5FF8CEC4EFAFC375BFACD" authority="Gil &amp; Ramil, 2021" authorityName="Gil &amp; Ramil" authorityYear="2021" box="[874,1079,1306,1332]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Halopterididae" genus="Monostaechoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="23" pageNumber="72" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis id="51B23F55FFA5FF8CEC4EFAFC375BFACD" box="[874,1079,1306,1332]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="72">Monostaechoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="4A81822EFFA5FF8CEB67FAFC37D8FACD" box="[1091,1204,1306,1332]" pageId="23" pageNumber="72" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, there is a ‘true axis’ represented by a stem or primary hydrocladium bearing several secondary hydrocladia irregularly disposed along the same axis. This branching pattern is clearly different from that displayed by 
<taxonomicName id="A4C698C4FFA5FF8CEF99FA76320AFA53" authorityName="Allman" authorityYear="1877" box="[189,358,1424,1450]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Halopterididae" genus="Monostaechas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="23" pageNumber="72" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="51B23F55FFA5FF8CEF99FA76320AFA53" box="[189,358,1424,1450]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="72">Monostaechas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, supporting the creation of a new genus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6379E347FFA5FF8CEF99FA303238F99E" blockId="23.[188,1399,1494,1639]" pageId="23" pageNumber="72">
The colonies of 
<taxonomicName id="A4C698C4FFA5FF8CEE5CFA303071FA09" authority="Nutting, 1906" authorityName="Nutting" authorityYear="1906" box="[376,797,1494,1520]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Halopterididae" genus="Monostaechas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="23" pageNumber="72" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="fisheri">
<emphasis id="51B23F55FFA5FF8CEE5CFA30311DFA09" box="[376,625,1494,1520]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="72">Monostaechas fisheri</emphasis>
Nutting, 1906
</taxonomicName>
, recently redescribed by 
<bibRefCitation id="07579EB6FFA5FF8CEB64FA30361DFA09" author="Galea H. R. &amp; Maggioni D." box="[1088,1393,1494,1520]" pageId="23" pageNumber="72" pagination="1 - 58" refId="ref21587" refString="Galea H. R. &amp; Maggioni D. 2020. Plumularioid hydroids (Cnidaria: Hydrozoa) from off New Caledonia collected during KANACONO and KANADEEP expeditions of the French Tropical Deep-Sea Benthos Program. European Journal of Taxonomy 708: 1 - 58. https: // doi. org / 10.5852 / ejt. 2020.708" type="journal article" year="2020">Galea &amp; Maggioni (2020)</bibRefCitation>
, show another ramification pattern, different from that met with in 
<taxonomicName id="A4C698C4FFA5FF8CECF8FA1B37C5F9EE" authority="In" authorityName="Gil &amp; Ramil" authorityYear="2021" box="[988,1193,1533,1559]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Halopterididae" genus="Monostaechoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="23" pageNumber="72" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis id="51B23F55FFA5FF8CECF8FA1B37C5F9EE" box="[988,1193,1533,1559]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="72">Monostaechoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="4A81822EFFA5FF8CEB97FA18364CF9E1" box="[1203,1312,1534,1560]" pageId="23" pageNumber="72" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
In this case, the stem is devoid of hydrothecae and the lateral ramification builds a true sympodium (see 
<bibRefCitation id="07579EB6FFA5FF8CEA01F9C33390F99E" author="Billard A." pageId="23" pageNumber="72" pagination="1 - 115" refId="ref19733" refString="Billard A. 1913. Les hydroides de l'expedition du Siboga, I. Plumulariidae. Siboga-Expeditie 7: 1 - 115." type="journal article" year="1913">Billard 1913</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 7).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6379E347FFA5FF8CEF99F974378EF810" blockId="23.[187,1399,1682,2025]" pageId="23" pageNumber="72">
The same 
<typeStatus id="BC7D5DE5FFA5FF8CEE12F9753205F954" box="[310,361,1683,1709]" pageId="23" pageNumber="72">type</typeStatus>
of ramification found in 
<taxonomicName id="A4C698C4FFA5FF8CEDB5F9743032F955" authority="Gil &amp; Ramil, 2021" authorityName="Gil &amp; Ramil" authorityYear="2021" box="[657,862,1682,1708]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Halopterididae" genus="Monostaechoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="23" pageNumber="72" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis id="51B23F55FFA5FF8CEDB5F9743032F955" box="[657,862,1682,1708]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="72">Monostaechoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="4A81822EFFA5FF8CEC42F97530BEF954" box="[870,978,1683,1709]" pageId="23" pageNumber="72" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
was also described in specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="A4C698C4FFA5FF8CEF99F95C31E6F92D" authority="(Gmelin, 1791)" baseAuthorityName="Gmelin" baseAuthorityYear="1791" box="[189,650,1722,1748]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Halopterididae" genus="Antennella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="23" pageNumber="72" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="secundaria">
<emphasis id="51B23F55FFA5FF8CEF99F95C32A4F92D" box="[189,456,1722,1748]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="72">Antennella secundaria</emphasis>
(Gmelin, 1791)
</taxonomicName>
collected from 
<collectingCountry id="1BD1A3D7FFA5FF8CEC6EF95C30D0F92D" box="[842,956,1722,1748]" name="Indonesia" pageId="23" pageNumber="72">Indonesia</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="07579EB6FFA5FF8CECE9F95C37EBF92D" author="Billard A." box="[973,1159,1722,1748]" pageId="23" pageNumber="72" pagination="1 - 115" refId="ref19733" refString="Billard A. 1913. Les hydroides de l'expedition du Siboga, I. Plumulariidae. Siboga-Expeditie 7: 1 - 115." type="journal article" year="1913">Billard 1913: 8</bibRefCitation>
, pl. 1 figs 2–3), the 
<collectingCountry id="1BD1A3D7FFA5FF8CEF99F9073256F902" box="[189,314,1761,1787]" name="Seychelles" pageId="23" pageNumber="72">Seychelles</collectingCountry>
(Millard &amp; Bouillon 1973: 78) and 
<collectingCountry id="1BD1A3D7FFA5FF8CEDF7F907300AF902" box="[723,870,1761,1787]" name="South Africa" pageId="23" pageNumber="72">South Africa</collectingCountry>
(Millard 1975: 334), suggesting the existence of other undescribed species within this genus. Both 
<bibRefCitation id="07579EB6FFA5FF8CEC07F8EF30A6F8DA" author="Billard A." box="[803,970,1801,1827]" pageId="23" pageNumber="72" pagination="1 - 115" refId="ref19733" refString="Billard A. 1913. Les hydroides de l'expedition du Siboga, I. Plumulariidae. Siboga-Expeditie 7: 1 - 115." type="journal article" year="1913">Billard (1913)</bibRefCitation>
and Millard (1975) pointed out that, in these colonies, the main axis is formed by the first hydrocladium, and does not originate from the basal part of successive hydrocladia, excluding these materials from 
<taxonomicName id="A4C698C4FFA5FF8CECCDF8BE37FEF88B" authorityName="Allman" authorityYear="1877" box="[1001,1170,1880,1906]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Halopterididae" genus="Monostaechas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="23" pageNumber="72" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="51B23F55FFA5FF8CECCDF8BE37FEF88B" box="[1001,1170,1880,1906]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="72">Monostaechas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Ramified colonies assigned to 
<taxonomicName id="A4C698C4FFA5FF8CEE69F866329EF860" baseAuthorityName="Gmelin" baseAuthorityYear="1791" box="[333,498,1919,1946]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Halopterididae" genus="Antennella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="23" pageNumber="72" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="secundaria">
<emphasis id="51B23F55FFA5FF8CEE69F866329EF860" box="[333,498,1919,1946]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="72">A. secundaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were also described by 
<bibRefCitation id="07579EB6FFA5FF8CEC31F8663713F860" author="Vervoort W. &amp; Vasseur P." box="[789,1151,1919,1946]" pageId="23" pageNumber="72" pagination="3 - 98" refId="ref26238" refString="Vervoort W. &amp; Vasseur P. 1977. Hydroids from French Polynesia with notes on distribution and ecology. Zoologische Verhandelingen, Leiden 159: 3 - 98." type="journal article" year="1977">Vervoort &amp; Vasseur (1977: 66</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 28b), 
<bibRefCitation id="07579EB6FFA5FF8CEA27F89932C2F83B" author="Ryland J. S. &amp; Gibbons M. J." pageId="23" pageNumber="72" pagination="525 - 560" refId="ref25042" refString="Ryland J. S. &amp; Gibbons M. J. 1991. Intertidal and shallow water hydroids from Fiji, II. Plumulariidae and Aglaopheniidae. Memoirs of the Queensland Museum 30 (3): 525 - 560." type="journal article" year="1991">Ryland &amp; Gibbons (1991: 526</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 1a) and 
<bibRefCitation id="07579EB6FFA5FF8CED68F8413074F838" author="Calder D. R." box="[588,792,1959,1985]" pageId="23" pageNumber="72" pagination="1 - 85" refId="ref20205" refString="Calder D. R. 1997. Shallow-water hydroids of Bermuda: superfamily Plumularioidea. Life Sciences Contributions of the Royal Ontario Museum 161: 1 - 85." type="journal article" year="1997">Calder (1997: 30</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 7a), but, in all cases, the ramification fits well with a sympodial pattern and was clearly different from that in 
<taxonomicName id="A4C698C4FFA5FF8CEC87F828371CF811" authority="Gil &amp; Ramil, 2021" authorityName="Gil &amp; Ramil" authorityYear="2021" box="[931,1136,1998,2024]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Halopterididae" genus="Monostaechoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="23" pageNumber="72" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis id="51B23F55FFA5FF8CEC87F828371CF811" box="[931,1136,1998,2024]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="72">Monostaechoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="4A81822EFFA5FF8CEB53F829378EF810" box="[1143,1250,1999,2025]" pageId="23" pageNumber="72" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
